Produced CDs were characterized by TEM, SEM, XPS, and Raman spectroscopy (Fig. 3
                     ). According to the XPS analysis all the CD samples contained about 30 at.% of oxygen regardless of the precursor type, synthesis temperature, and oxidation time (Fig. 3a). At the same time, different chemical states of carbon and, especially, of nitrogen atoms were revealed by XPS in the CDs synthesized from different precursors (Fig. 3b, c). As expected, higher intensities of the components at 286.4 and 287.6 eV in the C1s spectrum of A-800-3 indicate higher percentages of CN and CN bonds in this sample. The small fraction of the sp2-C component in this spectrum and its absence in the spectrum of the N-doped sample is explained by the presence of large number of functionalities. Neighboring heteroatoms may increase the C1s binding energy of sp2-C atoms and broaden the peaks at 285.0 and 284.4 eV making their separation more difficult [13–15]. The component at 285.0 eV can include the contribution not only from sp3-bonded carbon atoms but also from the part of sp2
                     -hybridized carbon atoms bonded to carboxyl/ester or nitrogen containing groups, which decreases the relative area of the component at 284.4 eV. Thus, we can propose that all the samples contained sp2-C but in the case of N-doped CDs the carbon core was more defective, which is typical for doped graphene materials. The peak of carboxyl species dominates in the C1s spectra of both doped and undoped samples but in the latter case it can be fitted by two components attributed to protonated and unprotonated groups. The presence of unprotonated groups can be explained by the formation of the ammonia salt under neutralization of the CD solution after oxidation. The N1s spectra of both N-doped and pristine CDs testify to the presence of pyrroles/amines, quarternary N, and N-oxides. In the case of pristine CDs these components resulted from the products of ammonia neutralization and from nitration of the carbon surface at the oxidation stage. The additional component observed in the N1s spectrum of N-doped CDs corresponds to amides. The presence of this component agrees with the oxidation-induced transformation of pyridinic and pyrrolic N species into pyridone groups observed in our previous works [15,16].
